    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my tomato plants are looking kind of sickly. the leaves on the bottom are turning yellow and falling off. what do you think is going on?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves on the bottom of tomato plants can be a sign of a few different issues. It's possible that your plants are experiencing a bit of a \"garden goblin\" problem, where the lower leaves are simply being eaten by pests like hornworms or aphids. You might want to inspect the underside of the leaves and stems for any signs of damage or infestation. \n\nAnother possibility is that your plants are getting too much water, causing the roots to rot and leading to yellowing leaves. It's a bit like when a human gets too much water and their skin starts to feel soggy and weak. \n\nIt's also worth checking the soil pH and nutrient levels, as tomatoes prefer a slightly acidic to neutral soil pH. If the soil is too alkaline or lacking in essential nutrients, it could be causing the yellowing leaves. You might need to add some organic matter like compost or manure to give your plants a boost. \n\nLastly, consider pruning the lower leaves to improve air circulation and reduce the risk of disease. This is a bit like how a gardener might remove a diseased branch from a tree to prevent the spread of disease. \n\nI hope these suggestions help you identify the issue and get your tomato",
      "source": "target",
